  </div></section>
  <section class="bg-gray-50 py-16"><div class="section max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-8 text-center">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What fire safety services are required for commercial buildings in New York, NY?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">New York enforces the NYC Fire Code (Local Law — not IFC). Requirements include fire extinguishers (NFPA 10), fire alarms (NFPA 72), sprinklers (NFPA 13/25), and kitchen suppression for commercial cooking (NFPA 96). NYC enforces its own local Fire Code — not the IFC or NY State Code. All fire protection work requires NYC-specific contractor licenses separate from state licensing.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often are fire inspections required in New York?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The Fire Department of New York (FDNY) conducts annual commercial property inspections. Fire extinguishers: monthly visual checks and annual professional inspection. Fire alarms: annual testing. Sprinklers: quarterly, semi-annual, and annual inspections. Kitchen suppression: semi-annual per NFPA 96.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What makes NYC's fire code different from other states and cities?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">New York City enforces the NYC Fire Code — a comprehensive local law that is materially different from the IFC used by most US cities and from the NY State Uniform Fire Code used elsewhere in New York. Key differences include: NYC-specific inspection certificate requirements (Certificates of Fitness) for fire system operators, unique filing requirements with the FDNY for certain systems, NYC-specific high-rise fire protection requirements, mandatory fire safety and evacuation plans for most commercial occupancies, and contractor licensing through the NYC Department of Buildings — separate from NYS licensing. Buildings in the outer boroughs are subject to the same NYC Fire Code as Manhattan, enforced by the same FDNY Bureau of Fire Prevention.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Do restaurants in New York need special fire suppression systems?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Yes. All commercial cooking producing grease-laden vapors requires a wet chemical suppression system per NFPA 96, plus a Class K extinguisher within 30 feet of cooking equipment. Systems must be inspected semi-annually by a licensed technician.</p></div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 border border-gray-200"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who enforces fire codes in New York, NY?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The Fire Department of New York (FDNY) enforces fire codes within New York limits. The NYS Office of Fire Prevention and Control (OFPC) licenses fire protection contractors at (518) 474-6746.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>
  <section class="py-16"><div class="section text-center max-w-2xl">
